segments.text: Okay, you were giving impressions of Dr. Calhoun.
My relationship with him started in the early 60s.
The Department of Commerce, the U.S. Department of Commerce, started what they called an Office of Technical Services, MTS.
And what they would do is they would provide you funding to answer inquiries from industry in your state.
So Dr. Calhoun created, at that time, what he called the State Technical Services Institute.
He asked me to serve as director of that, which I did.
And so I had some connection with them.
But the real connection, I guess, come was when the Sea Grant program got done.
I had quite a hunk of that Sea Grant program at one time.
And that come down there in the late 60s as well.
So I remember it had to be before 73.
And I did a lot of work with the Sea Grant program.
because I used my industrial economics staff.
It's been perfect to do all the economic studies along the coast and things of that nature.
And OTS had gone out of business, by the way.
Off-technical service had gone out of business.
And then I got in on the Sea Grant program.
And of course, we run all those things.
So that's really the period between 65 and 73 is when I got well acquired.
Make believe that I had never seen
John Calhoun described him physically and his style.
I wish I had a picture.
I could just give it to you.
Dr. Calhoun was probably the best, the most diversified, intelligent individual that I have ever met in my life.
Dr. Calhoun could grasp things rapidly.
I don't know whether he did a lot of reading on these things before I come in contact with him or not, but he was always very well versed.
My experience with him was through the State Technical Institute and through the Sea Grant Program.
And I always felt that Dr. Calhoun was a very easy person to talk to.
I never have seen Dr. Now, some people have told me they've seen Dr. Calhoun mad.
I've never seen him mad.
Never had in my life.
But we've become pretty close, I do in those years, on different things.
We attended a lot of conferences together.
I did a lot of studies.
And then one day out of the clear blue sky in 1973, on a Thursday afternoon, I was working away, and I got this phone call.
It was Dr. Whitman.
And Dr. Williams said, you know, now, I believe I told you before, I was having my industrial conference start Monday.
And I had the governor coming over to get the welcome address, which I had every year.
And Dr. Williams said, Jim, I'd like to talk to you in just a few minutes.
And he did, and that's when I got to work.
He said, fine.
I went on down to his office.
And after about five minutes of shaking hands and things, he said, you know, we have a vacancy as director of the Indian State Service.
that we want to create in the Office of Continuing Education.
And he says, I'd like for you to get those done.
Now, tell me about this man, Jack Williams.
Well, of course, Jack Williams and Dr. Calhoun were very close.
I mean, business-wise, I don't know about political-wise, but they were always there.
They had a lot of respect for each other.
So I said, well, Dr. Williams, I didn't even know there was a place.
I had the job, but I really enjoyed it.

getting bigger every day and getting more statewide and that's the recognition i said i i'd have to think about a little bit he said well what do you do you need anything to think about i said yes i said i want to copy the budget i said i want to see what kind of budget they have where their sources of money is coming from so he got on the phone and he called fred benson if i'm not mistaken it might have been calvin but he called somebody
and told me he had been dragged into the office, and he said, I'd like to get you a bunch of stuff here for the internet attention service.
And so he got them out about half a week.
And so we just did a few minutes, and he said, well, when do you think we can get back together?
And I said, we'll get back here on Monday morning.
I said, I have all Saturday and Sunday.
We'll get back Monday morning.
So he said, well, just give me a ring Monday morning when you're ready.
And I did.
Somewhere you just can't do without it.
And I didn't get to until, we couldn't get together until about 3 o'clock that afternoon.
But I went there and I told him what my problem was.
And I had, you know, because I didn't do anything.
I said, you know, if I'm going to do this, I need this, I need this, I need this, I need this, I need this, this, this.
Got down to the bottom line.
The most important thing, I had to have total control of all the people in the organization.
And that I was going to be fair with them.
I was going to evaluate each one of them.
But if they didn't fit into the organization, if I'm going to plan for this, then we're going to have to find somebody that will fill that spot.
But anyway, it went on like that.
And I had to listen pretty long.
When I got through, he says, is that all?
I said, yes, sir.
He said, you haven't asked for nothing.
He said, you haven't asked for nothing?
He said, no.
I think he said, you haven't asked for nothing.
You can't get it.
And so I said, OK.
So then he called Fred Benson in California.
I told him that I'd accepted the job.
And I guess Calhoun could tell you more about it from now on.
As far as you know, he had talked with each of them in depth.
Oh, yes.
Oh, I'm quite sure of that.

I mean, Dr. Williams would have done... No, and another thing I had, see, I had a lot of research projects in that industry, industrial economics research, and this was in August when he called me in.
And I told him, I said, I couldn't possibly accept the job until December 12th.
Really?
Because I had sponsors out here that supported me for years.
And I said, well, that'd be fun.
That didn't bother any.
Describe the extension service when you took over.
What was it?
How big was it?
Where was it?
Well, it was in the old American Legion Hall, where Bob White walked before he moved out there.
That used to be just an old building there.
Do you remember that?
Or was it already down when you got here?
I don't know.

it i was here do you remember where the headquarters of bob white's wasn't until just about a year ago no no well you know where the uh you know where the farmer student association building is now it used to be that old wooden building right across the street oh across the street yeah yeah yeah yeah yeah yeah over there by the police station yeah yeah well i didn't know anybody
I didn't know anybody in Indian Peninsula except Ernie Winochek.
The only reason I knew him, he had .
And I had met him through Buddy Williams.
And Buddy Williams, he and Ernie were pretty good friends.
But he's the only one I knew.
And so when I took over, they took action at the October 4th meeting.
Ford Hall made the motion, Ms. Wilson seconded it.
This is 73?
Yes, 73.
I forgot to go with you.
But this meeting was in October before the meeting.
And so when that was announced, it would come out in the paper and everything by the day.
Well, by the way, Dr. Knight, you know, the dean of medicine, was approved the same day I was approved to direct the Institute of Patient Service.
His picture's on the front page of the Eagle on one side and mine's on the other.
And I just saw when they fixed that monument or whatever it was.
But...
When I went over to the Engineering Extension Service, it had a budget of about $1.5 million, and they had about $50 million employed.
Where were they based?
All of them here?
Yeah, at that time.
They were a very...
They weren't up to date.
There was not an area that you could find that they don't.
They taught without lesson plans.
They didn't have any technical manuals.
It's a training organization.
But they have 51 employees and a little over about a million and a half dollars budget.
But their budget comes, one-third comes from Texas Education Agency, one-third comes directly from Appropriations, and then they've got one-third of their budget from the city.
And that was the third, third, and third.
Well, you've got to realize, the engineering attention service was an overarching section.
And most of the employees were in there since their first job.
Anyway, when it was announced, they had a Dr. Mansfield, who was the associate director.
And that was the final person that you ever want to meet.
But he had been led to believe, either through himself or through Mr. Bearden.
See, Mr. Bearden had been director, and he retired.
That he was going to be the director.
Well, by the way, when I become director, well, I'll be the director.
But anyway, and all of them in the engineering and attention service was, you know, shocked that he didn't get it.
So the first day I took over, December 1, 1973, I stayed away from it until I
My wife went in for her third malignancy surgery.
She was operating from that morning, the first day I had to go.
Two important events.
Very important events.
I stayed with my wife.
I called Dr. Calhoun, which I don't know who I called.
I don't know who I called.
But anyway, they knew where I was at.
And I stayed with her all that day.
We were talking to Quade.
And we had a doctor out of Houston come up.
And that was her third surgery.
So after they got through with the surgery, it was in about five hours, Dr. Quaid come out and told me, he said, I don't have much hope for you.
He said, but we're going to send her down to Houston and start taking chemotherapy.
No, I'm not going to dwell on this.
Anyway, after the third operation, my wife had about all the operations she wanted.
But anyway, they made an appointment for me to go see this doctor down at the hospital in Houston.
And I got away at the point.
It was 1.30 in the afternoon.
My wife and I walked in, and I checked in, and he shut the door, and I stayed outside.
And about 20 minutes, or 15 minutes, he'd come out and said, I'm sorry.
I said, your wife won't let me touch you.
He said, she's not going to take you from up there.
I said,
And he said, unless I get to examine it.
So we went in and he said, come on in.
I said, are you sure you made up the money?
I said, how much did I owe him?
He said, $35.
I wrote him a check.
And that was in 1973.
Can you imagine that?
But going back to where did primarily geographically, where did
When you took over, where were they doing the instruction that they were?
They were going out in motels.
No, but where was it?
Was it in the Houston area?
Oh, it was all over the state.
But it wasn't concentrated in one?
No, no.
OK. No, no.
See, they were doing all the training for rural electric co-ops, and their linemen training and things of this nature.
They did a lot of training for the Texas Telephone Association.
But see, they were getting subsidized.
Right.
Give more examples of that.
Okay, and the law enforcement, all the state and law enforcement, water and wastewater, they did all the training for water and wastewater in the cities.
Of course, we had the fire protection, we had the extension part of it, and then we had the fire field.
Fireman Training Center was all part of that?
Oh, yeah.
That was it.
That was the biggest part.
But they used volunteer instructors.
They only had four people on the full-time staff of the farm.
They'd go to town, they'd just get somebody on the farm to volunteer.
Was there one client that was by far the key one, the biggest?
Well, the rural electric co-op, of course, the organization was so small, they only had 50, 55 people.
But the rural electric co-ops,

and the tucson telephone association and the water departments of the cities and the law enforcement and the law those were your it was all sizable but but to kind of put this thing in perspective when i left there we had 400 employees in a 39 million dollar budget was only getting 3 million in general revenue 36 million was coming in fees and contracts now wait what give me those numbers again
When I took over, it was around 51, I think, employees, about 1.5 million.
When I left on December, I mean on January the 31st, 1992, we had a $39 million budget we had for employees.
And of that budget, how much did y'all...
Ten percent.
We got three million and something in general revenue.
The rest you brought in.
Just as in fees and contracts.
All right.
When you started out, you were primarily serving small-town needs...
rural areas, and city water departments in your small town, city water departments, small town lawns.
And the telephone companies were the co-ops.
All right, let's see.
When you took over, were there any key office staff members that you came to rely on?
I'm talking about the people in the office.
I lined them up real fast.
I had to bring them in.
As I told you, Dr. Mansfield was a fine person, and there must have been a shock to his system because he had never heard of me.
And, of course, he just never would.
Well, he had a different philosophy.
His philosophy and my philosophy was completely 100% different.
I was used to the soft money operation.
I've always had the soft money operation.
I liked it.
It gave me a lot of latitude.
They didn't like it.
It was a threat to their jobs.
Scared them.
Threatened their jobs.
So, but then another thing I asked Dr. Williams when I took over, I had to have a new headquarters office.
I had to have another office in England.
I never did go down to that one, but I was up on the eighth floor at the top, because that's where I had the Director of Continuing Education, and I had that whole eighth floor at the top.
Of the Rudder Tower?
Yeah.
So, that's where, that was my headquarters for both Austin Continuing Education and Continuing Education.
All right, when you took over,

in terms of reporting you reported to dr calhoun and fred in which order all three of us worked very well all right on paper was it to benson or was it to both on paper okay uh see i got funding from junior education texas university
All right, let's go back and talk about this man, Benson.
He's a Kansan, I think, didn't he come?
Kent State.
And tell me about his working style and so forth.
Well, you never did leave a meeting with Fred Benson that you didn't know where he stood.
He wasn't a bit bashful to pick up the phone and say, Jim, what's this I hear about so-and-so's?
It explained it to him.
That was the end of it, I guess, for me at all.
You know, we had our ground rules.
I set my ground rules with him.
What do you expect?
What kind of report do you want?
When do you want me to inform you of something?
Give me some guidelines.
Because I don't have time to tell you everything I do.
And you don't have time to listen to everything I do.
Give me your guidelines.
You know what Mr. Benson's answer was to that?
keep me informed on the matter you think that I could have some input on.
I never called them.
Not that, you know, I just, I just never had a reason.
I can say the same thing about California.
All right, now, officially, the Extension, the Extension, Engineering Extension Service was part of the Texas A&M University and of the system.
No, the Engineering Extension Service
was always a part of the system all right during those years with Williams and Calhoun and Benson did it matter system or campus and how you operated when you wanted to communicate with them
whom did you have to go through to get to Calhoun or to Benson?
Nobody except their secretary.
They all, you always, he had the same, they had the same thing with me.
I mean, we never, I never had one minute that I ever thought.
All right, as you think back on those first years, what were some key decisions that were made by you or anybody else?
Retain to the system.

or pertaining to the work of the of the extension of the extension of the well I'm not being derogatory but I had to have people that would grow I had you know I had maybe two people with college degrees Dr. Mansfield might have had one or two others the rest of them was all non-degree people they had one title it was all called

instructors so my first thing that I did when I went in there by January the 1st I had a I had a study conducted on what their title should be I had told me exactly what the qualification should be as far as education experience and I even I had no pay range everybody made the same if you're an instructor you make the same or give or take
So the first thing we did, we give them something to, and then in February of that year, I had a meeting in Wyandale with the whole staff.
Day and a half, two days of meetings.
At which time, I give them a copy of what I call management by objective.
How we was gonna run the engineering services, what part they was gonna play, what was expected of them, and so forth and so on.
And that didn't go too well then.
But anyway, there was a few,

They'd all been in together.
Here's a damn stranger.

They didn't, you know, it had never been as fun.

This is for the engineer detention services.
Recommendation of Dr. Williams to Fred Benson.
I kept Fred informed on it.
He told me to take it to Dr. Williams.
On the pay scale.
And they had about, I'd say they had about $500,000 in the services.
Engineer detention services had about $500,000.
So we automatically, if they had the qualifications, they could go into this pay status.
If they didn't,
to find somebody that had those qualifications and so forth and so on.
But we'd give them each title, training specialist, associate training specialist, assistant training specialist, you know, give them to separate them.
But, what was the question?
Well, it was about key decisions.
Okay.
That's how the decisions were made.
And then once we got that thing in line, and unfortunately, the borough got them plans, you know,
Decided to take retirement.
He was about six or seven years old.
And he decided to take retirement.
And he took retirement.
Three days later, he died.
He died of a heart attack.
But he'd had bypass surgery.
So that moved that phase, whatever you want to call it, out.
And then I brought in a new man as associate director.
I brought in Neil Pratt right off.
He was a young engineer.
How do you spell his last name?
He was a young man.
He was with TTI.
And how did he come about being with us?
TTI was getting into public works training.
Well, I had created a center for public works.
And I picked up the paper one Saturday morning.
There was TTI announcing their public works.
So I got a hold of Fred.
I said, Fred, we've got a problem.
He said, what's the problem?
I told him.
He said, I'll take care of that Monday morning.
So he had Jack Keese in.
And all of a sudden, he could get out of public work.
That's an extension activity.
That's not a research activity.
And so Milton Rutte was in that position for TPI.
So I just transferred him and one other TPI staff member.
Their whole people worked in public work.
And it turned out that Milton was a very good engineer, and a very smart individual, and a very, very good driver.
Hard work, very hard work.
So I brought him over to the social director.
Well, that made all the rest of the, well, I didn't do it by all.
He's there a year, a year and a half.
So I brought him, you know, I observed him for a time.
But that's how that got started.
But when you have to have a decision made, it took me less than five minutes to get it.
I could call Benson.
He'd say, well, what did you do?
Or what do you want to do?
Or I could call Calhoun.
Calhoun wasn't as quick on the draw as Benson was, but he was still very quick.
You know what I mean?
Did you ever get the impression that either one of them ever made a snap judgment without thinking it through?
Let's see, back to other decisions.
Because you're in charge for 19 years.
Other decisions that you now look back on and say, those were key decisions we made.
Well, one key decision we made happened.
You always build on your strength.
We had a reputation in the fire department, all over the state.
I could contact every legislator with one phone call.
So I said, that's our fight.
So the first thing I did, I put about $150,000 in the FARC.
I said, look, we don't have any roads in here.
We don't have any training aids out there or exhibits.
So I put that right on.
And that was located then where it is now, just east of Easterwood Airport.
Right.
And Calhoun was responsible for getting that location along the four optical vision attention center.
But anyway.
So we started building on that.
Then I said, okay, what's your second strength?
Well, my second strength was electronics, but I had a man in electronics that, you know, had no education to speak of.
So his name was Art.
A fine person.
All these people out in town, you know, fine people, and that wasn't the problem with them was that they didn't have the background to do what was necessary.
So I replaced him right off with Dr. Lloyd Fite.
F-I-T-E. F-I-T-E.
He was Dick Renardi's...
Andy, man, you knew me, you know?
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.
So, Dick would already call me up one day.
He said, Jim, he said, Lloyd didn't get his tenure.
And he said, you know, he said, do you want to get out of the academic park or whatever?
And he said, is there any way you can take him half-time?
I said, sure, I can take him half-time.
Well, I took Lloyd over and it was half-time with other spending.
That was in February.
It was half-time September 1st.
He'd go on a phone call.
We had it out to read with the nurse.
And so we then started leaning pretty heavy on electronics, and we got that thing built up.
We had a gentleman in me in the rural electric co-ops.
At one time, the same gentleman was over at the rural electric co-op training and the Texas Telephone Association training.
So when he retired, I saw that was my strength coming.
In the meantime, I got to be very, very well informed and acquainted with folks
with people on the Texas, Texas Temporal Association Board, and the Electric Fire Department Board.
And they were lobbying for me.
The Rural Electric Corps would take the engineering and maintenance service with their lobbyists for funding.
And same thing with Texas Temporal Association.
So I said, well, you know, that's a growth area.
Maybe not Rural Electric, but, you know, we've got others.
So we started tying in there with GTE.
Started tying in with several others.
Got all their training materials.
They'd give me every bit of their training material.
We could use, reproduce.
But at that time, see, none of my people had nothing, no training material.
So we got that from the telephone train, from the telephone.
Then we started getting the power train, electric power.
The real electric co-op didn't have any, but Houston Light and Power at that time had plenty.
Texas, the big one that really helped me out on my electric training was Texas Fire and Light.
It's now Texas Utility.
That's how we built the thing.
We took those growth areas.
And then after, you know, we evaluated them, and if they had no growth potential, you know, you say, you know, we maybe ought to take them out, which we did.
We did away with three or four divisions.
What were they?
Oh, boy.
They were always one-man operations.
We had, well, one thing we did,
Fire had to have this material, and I took that directly away from fire.
I started to have this training, a whole division of it.
But Al Sterling, a very fine guy, he was a Coast Guard colonel, retired.
He had his master's degree from MIT.
When he retired, we brought him up here with both divisions and also put that under fire.
We did the same thing with management training.
We used to have two levels of management training.
One was for the very bold level training.
So then we just started to get to the higher level, the supervisory training.
So I let that lower division just go and just started what I call supervisory training.
And I'm sure there's five or six others, but I didn't write all of them.
But we ended up, we started out, we had five divisions, and we ended up with 17 divisions.
Our staff, the professionals first is the support staff, and we're about four to one.
Every professional has about one.
See, now that staff person had to do a lot of work while those people were traveling all over the state of Texas.
And they had to have strong staff people.
But it was about four to one.
Where, in the areas where you all worked, in what area, what work area, subject area, was it easiest to raise money, and which one was most difficult to support?
It was all, there was no difference.
Let me just tell you why.
We started centers about 10 years after I got there, about in 78, 79.
I put in my first center in San Antonio called South Central Texas Regional Training Center.
And at that time, Henry Cisneros was on the city council, and then Lenny made the marriage.
And they had a program over there that was under the junior college, and they were totally unhappy.
The city funded it, and they were totally unhappy
So the guy, the president of Central Junior College over there, Mr. Dr. Whelan, so they asked me to take it over.
I said, well, listen, we've got as much as we want.
I'll go talk to him.
Well, I'll go talk to him.
He was as happy as a lark to get it to me.
You can't get along with him.
But anyway, he had about a $300,000 a year program with him.
And so then when we took over South Central Region Training Center, whenever I did anything like that, I'll give everyone what they need.
You've got to provide me facilities.
Mm-hmm.
And you know what I mean?
We can't rent them.
We don't mean that.
We mean we want facilities built.
If you want the engineering facility to come in, we have to look the part and play the part.
And so we've got real nice facilities.
The city got it with EDA grant.
And the man in San Antonio gives 20 acres of land.
But anyway, we turned out to have a big thing.
So then when they redid the hemisphere area,
They wanted us to get, they wanted us to concentrate on electronics in that area.
So, wow, they built this beautiful big building, you know, right there in the chemistry room.
And we had a one 25-year lease, and before I left, I got two 25-year lease extensions, so that's 75 years.
But, oh.
When we put that in, that was our first cylinder.
And when I left that thing, it had about a $2 million in it.
So then the next thing I went in was North Texas.
And the next cylinder was in the West Texas area that was happening.
Now all these people were furnishing us these facilities.
And let's see, then Houston.
We went into the Houston area about the same time we went into
